{{notability|date=February 2017}} {{refimprove|date=May 2016}} The '''Chester Ronning Centre for the Study of Religion and Public Life''' is a [[research centre]] on the [[University of Alberta]]'s [[Augustana University College|Augustana Campus]] in [[Camrose, Alberta]]. It is the first such centre in a public university in Canada to focus on the intersection of religion and public life.
==Background== The Ronning Centre is named in for [[Chester Alvin Ronning]], Canadian diplomat and principal of Camrose Lutheran College from 1927 to 1942. The Chester Ronning Centre for the Study of Religion and Public Life grew from the merger of [[Augustana University College]] with the [[University of Alberta]] in 2004. The Centre's activities involve a diversity of communities. It seeks to enhance debate on contested issues through lively discussion.<ref>https://www.augustana.ualberta.ca/research/centres/ronningcentre/aboutus/ University of Alberta, Augustana Campus, Chester Ronning Centre for the Study of Religion and Public Life</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cardus.ca/comment/article/765/qa-with-david-j-goa-director-chester-ronning-centre-for-the-study-of-religion-and-public-life-university-of-alberta/|title=Q&A with David J. Goa, Director, Chester Ronning Centre for the Study of Religion and Public Life, University of Alberta|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://religionanddiversity.ca/en/research-centres/prairies/|title=Religion and Diversity Project - The Prairies|publisher=}}</ref>
