'''Edgeoscopy''' is a method of identification through the examination of the unique details and characteristics found along the edges of individual [[fingerprint]] ridges. These characteristics are the result of the alignment and shape of the individual ridge units and the relationship between them, as well as the effects of [[Sweat pore|pore]]s that are close to the edge of the ridges. These shapes are only of use when quality of the [[friction]] ridges found in both the latent fingerprint and the exemplar print is high. The method was pioneered by Salil Chatterjee in 1962, who created it while researching the possibility of a new [[criminal]] identification method.<ref>The Fingerprint Science and Ridgeology, Kuhn, Kurt E.</ref>

